                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-03-02T17:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 2, 1923—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 2—9:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>71. Is President’s proclamation of March 4, 1922,<note n="34" xml:id="d461fn34">
                        <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_726">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 726</ref>.</note> regarding export arms
                    and ammunition of war from the United States to China applicable to the
                    Philippine Islands?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
